### Interview Tip
> Always mention **resumable uploads** for video. It shows you understand real-world constraints: mobile users on flaky networks uploading gigabytes of video. Google resumable upload protocol is a well-known standard -- referencing it shows practical knowledge.

## API Design

### Post Creation with Pre-signed URLs

Instead of proxying large image uploads through the API server, use pre-signed URLs:

**Step 1: Request upload URL**
```
POST /api/v1/posts/upload-url
{
  "content_type": "image/jpeg",
  "file_size": 2048000
}
```

**Response:**
```json
{
  "upload_url": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/ig-uploads/...",
  "upload_id": "upl_abc123",
  "expires_in": 300
}
```

**Step 2: Upload image directly to S3**
```
PUT {upload_url}
Content-Type: image/jpeg
Body: <raw image bytes>
```

**Step 3: Create post with uploaded image**
```
POST /api/v1/posts
{
  "upload_id": "upl_abc123",
  "caption": "Beautiful sunset! #travel #photography",
  "location": {"lat": 48.8566, "lng": 2.3522, "name": "Paris, France"}
}
```

**Response:**
```json
{
  "id": "post_789",
  "user": {"id": "user_123", "username": "traveler"},
  "image_url": "https://cdn.instagram.com/p/789/1080.jpg",
  "caption": "Beautiful sunset! #travel #photography",
  "like_count": 0,
  "comment_count": 0,
  "created_at": "2025-06-01T15:30:00Z"
}
```

### Feed API with Cursor Pagination

```
GET /api/v1/feed?cursor=eyJ0cyI6MTcxNzI0NTAwMH0=&limit=20
```

**Response:**
```json
{
  "posts": [
    {
      "id": "post_789",
      "user": {"id": "user_123", "username": "traveler", "avatar_url": "..."},
      "image_url": "https://cdn.instagram.com/p/789/1080.jpg",
      "caption": "Beautiful sunset!",
      "like_count": 1423,
      "comment_count": 89,
      "liked_by_viewer": false,
      "created_at": "2025-06-01T15:30:00Z"
    }
  ],
  "next_cursor": "eyJ0cyI6MTcxNzI0NDAwMH0=",
  "has_more": true
}
```

**Why cursor pagination, not offset?**
- Offset pagination breaks with new posts being inserted (skipped or duplicated items)
- Cursor (timestamp-based) gives stable pagination regardless of new inserts
- The cursor is an encoded timestamp of the last seen post

### Python API Implementation

```python
from fastapi import FastAPI, Depends, Query
import base64, json

app = FastAPI()

@app.get("/api/v1/feed")
async def get_feed(
    user_id: str = Depends(get_current_user),
    cursor: str = Query(None),
    limit: int = Query(20, le=50),
):
    if cursor:
        cursor_data = json.loads(base64.b64decode(cursor))
        before_ts = cursor_data["ts"]
    else:
        before_ts = None

    post_ids = await feed_service.get_feed(
        user_id=user_id, before_ts=before_ts, limit=limit + 1
    )

    has_more = len(post_ids) > limit
    post_ids = post_ids[:limit]

    posts = await post_service.batch_get(post_ids)

    next_cursor = None
    if has_more and posts:
        next_cursor = base64.b64encode(
            json.dumps({"ts": posts[-1].created_at}).encode()
        ).decode()

    return {"posts": posts, "next_cursor": next_cursor, "has_more": has_more}
```

### Java API Implementation

```java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1")
public class FeedController {

    @GetMapping("/feed")
    public ResponseEntity<FeedResponse> getFeed(
            @RequestAttribute("userId") Long userId,
            @RequestParam(required = false) String cursor,
            @RequestParam(defaultValue = "20") int limit) {

        Long beforeTs = decodeCursor(cursor);
        List<Long> postIds = feedService.getFeed(userId, beforeTs, limit + 1);

        boolean hasMore = postIds.size() > limit;
        postIds = postIds.subList(0, Math.min(postIds.size(), limit));

        List<Post> posts = postService.batchGet(postIds);
        String nextCursor = hasMore ? encodeCursor(posts.get(posts.size() - 1)) : null;

        return ResponseEntity.ok(new FeedResponse(posts, nextCursor, hasMore));
    }
}
```

### Stories API

```
GET /api/v1/stories/feed
```

Stories differ from posts:
- TTL-based: automatically expire after 24 hours
- Served from Redis (not Cassandra)
- Grouped by user, not chronologically mixed

```json
{
  "story_reels": [
    {
      "user": {"id": "user_456", "username": "friend1"},
      "stories": [
        {"id": "story_1", "image_url": "...", "created_at": "...", "expires_at": "..."},
        {"id": "story_2", "image_url": "...", "created_at": "...", "expires_at": "..."}
      ],
      "seen": false
    }
  ]
}
```

### Rate Limiting

| Endpoint | Limit | Window |
|---|---|---|
| POST /posts | 50/day | 24 hours |
| POST /comments | 200/hour | 1 hour |
| POST /likes | 350/hour | 1 hour |
| GET /feed | 200/hour | 1 hour |
| POST /follows | 200/day | 24 hours |

### Interview Tips

> **Tip:** Pre-signed URLs for image upload is a must-mention. Proxying multi-MB images through your API server wastes bandwidth, CPU, and memory. With pre-signed URLs, the client uploads directly to S3 - your API server only handles the small metadata request. This is how every major platform handles file uploads.

## News Feed Generation (Fan-out)

### Fan-out-on-Write vs Fan-out-on-Read

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph Fan_out_Write[Fan-out-on-Write - Push Model]
        P1[User posts] --> W1[Write to all followers' feeds]
        W1 --> F1[Follower A feed]
        W1 --> F2[Follower B feed]
        W1 --> F3[Follower C feed]
    end

    subgraph Fan_out_Read[Fan-out-on-Read - Pull Model]
        R1[Follower opens feed] --> R2[Query all followed users' posts]
        R2 --> R3[Merge and rank]
    end
```

| Approach | Write Cost | Read Cost | Best For |
|---|---|---|---|
| Fan-out-on-Write | O(followers) per post | O(1) per feed read | Users with < 10K followers |
| Fan-out-on-Read | O(1) per post | O(following) per feed read | Users with millions of followers |
| **Hybrid** | **Varies** | **Varies** | **Production systems like Instagram** |

### The Celebrity Problem

If a user has 100M followers and posts once:
- Fan-out-on-write: 100M writes to Cassandra = minutes of delay
- This blocks the feed pipeline for other users

**Solution: Hybrid approach**
- Normal users (< 10K followers): fan-out-on-write (push)
- Celebrities (> 10K followers): fan-out-on-read (pull)
- Feed merge at read time combines both

### Hybrid Fan-out Implementation

```python
CELEBRITY_THRESHOLD = 10_000

class FanOutService:
    def __init__(self, cassandra, redis, kafka):
        self.cassandra = cassandra
        self.redis = redis
        self.kafka = kafka

    async def handle_new_post(self, post):
        follower_count = await self.get_follower_count(post.user_id)

        if follower_count < CELEBRITY_THRESHOLD:
            # Push model: write to all followers' feeds
            await self.fan_out_write(post)
        else:
            # Pull model: just index the post, followers will pull
            await self.index_celebrity_post(post)

    async def fan_out_write(self, post):
        followers = await self.get_all_followers(post.user_id)

        # Batch write to Cassandra (async, parallel)
        batch_size = 1000
        for i in range(0, len(followers), batch_size):
            batch = followers[i:i + batch_size]
            tasks = [
                self.cassandra.execute(
                    "INSERT INTO feed (user_id, post_id, author_id, created_at) "
                    "VALUES (%s, %s, %s, %s)",
                    (fid, post.id, post.user_id, post.created_at)
                )
                for fid in batch
            ]
            await asyncio.gather(*tasks)

        # Update Redis cache for active users
        active_followers = await self.get_active_followers(followers)
        for fid in active_followers:
            await self.redis.zadd(
                f"feed:{fid}",
                {str(post.id): post.created_at.timestamp()}
            )
```

### Java Fan-out Implementation

```java
@Service
public class FanOutService {

    private static final int CELEBRITY_THRESHOLD = 10_000;

    @Async
    public void handleNewPost(Post post) {
        int followerCount = followService.getFollowerCount(post.getUserId());

        if (followerCount < CELEBRITY_THRESHOLD) {
            fanOutOnWrite(post);
        } else {
            indexCelebrityPost(post);
        }
    }

    private void fanOutOnWrite(Post post) {
        List<Long> followers = followService.getAllFollowers(post.getUserId());

        List<List<Long>> batches = Lists.partition(followers, 1000);
        batches.parallelStream().forEach(batch -> {
            BatchStatement batchStmt = new BatchStatement();
            for (Long followerId : batch) {
                batchStmt.add(feedInsertStmt.bind(
                    followerId, post.getId(),
                    post.getUserId(), post.getCreatedAt()
                ));
            }
            cassandraSession.execute(batchStmt);
        });
    }
}
```

### Feed Merge at Read Time

```python
async def get_feed(user_id: int, before_ts: float, limit: int) -> list:
    # 1. Get pre-computed feed from Cassandra
    push_posts = await cassandra.execute(
        "SELECT post_id, created_at FROM feed "
        "WHERE user_id = %s AND created_at < %s "
        "ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT %s",
        (user_id, before_ts, limit)
    )

    # 2. Get celebrity posts (pull on read)
    celebrity_followees = await get_celebrity_followees(user_id)
    pull_posts = []
    for celeb_id in celebrity_followees:
        recent = await get_recent_posts(celeb_id, before_ts, limit=5)
        pull_posts.extend(recent)

    # 3. Merge and sort by timestamp
    all_posts = list(push_posts) + pull_posts
    all_posts.sort(key=lambda p: p.created_at, reverse=True)

    return all_posts[:limit]
```

### Feed Ranking

Modern Instagram does not show a pure chronological feed - it ranks by predicted engagement:

**Ranking signals:**
- **Recency:** Newer posts score higher
- **Relationship:** Posts from users you interact with frequently
- **Interest:** ML model predicts if you will engage with this content type
- **Popularity:** Like/comment velocity (trending posts boosted)

### Interview Tips

> **Tip:** The hybrid fan-out approach is the most important concept in this design. Normal users use fan-out-on-write for fast reads. Celebrities use fan-out-on-read to avoid writing to millions of feeds. At read time, merge both sources. This is how Instagram, Twitter, and Facebook actually work.

## Session 4: API Design & Real-Time Communication

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant R as Rider App
    participant GW as API Gateway
    participant RS as Ride Service
    participant MS as Matching Service
    participant D as Driver App

    R->>GW: POST /rides (pickup, dropoff)
    GW->>RS: createRide()
    RS->>MS: findDriver(pickup, rideType)
    MS-->>RS: driverId, ETA
    RS->>D: WebSocket: RIDE_REQUEST
    D->>RS: ACCEPT
    RS-->>GW: ride_id, driver, ETA
    GW-->>R: 201 Created

    loop Every 4 seconds
        D->>GW: WebSocket: location update
        GW->>R: WebSocket: driver location
    end
```

