### Cursor-Based Pagination

Twitter uses **cursor-based pagination** instead of offset-based for several reasons:

| Feature | Offset-Based | Cursor-Based |
|---------|-------------|-------------|
| New items during pagination | Duplicates or missed items | Consistent |
| Performance at high offsets | Slow (OFFSET 100000) | Fast (always indexed) |
| Real-time feeds | Broken by new inserts | Works correctly |
| Deletion during pagination | Shifts results | Unaffected |

```python
def get_timeline_with_cursor(user_id: str, cursor: str = None, count: int = 20):
    """Cursor is the last tweet_id seen (Snowflake IDs are time-sortable)."""
    if cursor:
        # Get tweets older than cursor
        tweet_ids = redis.zrevrangebyscore(
            f"timeline:{user_id}",
            max=int(cursor) - 1,
            min="-inf",
            start=0,
            num=count
        )
    else:
        tweet_ids = redis.zrevrange(f"timeline:{user_id}", 0, count - 1)

    has_more = len(tweet_ids) == count
    next_cursor = tweet_ids[-1] if has_more else None
    return {"tweets": hydrate(tweet_ids), "next_cursor": next_cursor, "has_more": has_more}
```

