### Performance Optimization Techniques

1. **Request coalescing**: Multiple clients requesting the same viral tweet results in a single backend fetch
2. **Prefetching**: Predict which timelines will be requested and warm the cache
3. **Compression**: Tweets are small but at billions of copies, compression saves TB of Redis memory
4. **Connection pooling**: Reuse connections to Redis and Manhattan

```java
// Request coalescing for hot tweets
public class RequestCoalescer<K, V> {
    private final ConcurrentHashMap<K, CompletableFuture<V>> inflight =
        new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public CompletableFuture<V> get(K key, Function<K, V> loader) {
        return inflight.computeIfAbsent(key, k -> {
            CompletableFuture<V> future = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(
                () -> loader.apply(k));
            future.whenComplete((v, ex) -> inflight.remove(k));
            return future;
        });
    }
}
```

> **Interview Tip:** When discussing scalability, always quantify. Do not just say "we will add more servers." Say "at 1.7M fan-out writes/sec, with each Redis node handling ~100K writes/sec, we need at least 17 primary nodes plus replicas, so approximately 50-60 Redis nodes for the fan-out layer alone."

