```java
@Service
public class RegionalFailoverManager {

    private final Map<String, RegionHealth> regionHealth = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 5000)
    public void healthCheck() {
        for (String region : List.of("us-east-1", "eu-west-1", "ap-south-1")) {
            try {
                HealthResponse health = regionalClient.healthCheck(region);
                regionHealth.put(region, new RegionHealth(
                    region, true,
                    health.getDbLagMs(),
                    health.getActiveConnections()
                ));
            } catch (Exception e) {
                regionHealth.put(region, RegionHealth.unhealthy(region));
            }
        }
    }

    public String getFailoverRegion(String primaryRegion) {
        // For financial data: manual failover only (to prevent split-brain)
        Map<String, String> failoverMap = Map.of(
            "us-east-1", "us-west-2",
            "eu-west-1", "eu-central-1",
            "ap-south-1", "ap-southeast-1"
        );

        String failover = failoverMap.get(primaryRegion);
        if (failover != null && regionHealth.getOrDefault(failover, RegionHealth.UNKNOWN).isHealthy()) {
            return failover;
        }

        throw new NoFailoverAvailableException(
            "No healthy failover for " + primaryRegion + ". Manual intervention required."
        );
    }
}
```

### Horizontal Scaling Strategy

| Component | Strategy | Notes |
|-----------|----------|-------|
| **API Servers** | Horizontal + LB | Stateless, auto-scale on CPU/request count |
| **Payment Service** | Horizontal with sticky sessions | Saga state in DB, not in memory |
| **PostgreSQL (Ledger)** | Vertical + read replicas | Cannot shard ledger easily; scale writes vertically |
| **PostgreSQL (Charges)** | Shard by merchant_id | Each shard holds all data for a set of merchants |
| **Redis (Idempotency)** | Cluster mode | Consistent hashing across nodes |
| **Kafka** | Partition by merchant_id | Ensures ordering per merchant |
| **Fraud ML Model** | Replicated instances | Same model loaded on every instance |

### Interview Tip

> For payment systems, explain why you use **manual failover** instead of automatic failover for the primary database. Automatic failover risks a **split-brain** scenario where two regions both think they are primary and process the same payment differently. In financial systems, it is better to have a brief outage (minutes) than to risk double-processing payments. This is a controversial but well-reasoned design decision that impresses interviewers.

